That’s a very old and very deep observation.

A thing is defined not only by its contents, but by its boundaries.

A sculptor removes stone as much as they add form. The statue is partly the marble that remains and partly the marble that is gone.

Language works this way:

* “Cat” means cat because it excludes dog, tree, cloud, and everything else.
* Every word carries a halo of things it is not.

Identity works this way too:

* Your values are partly the choices you make.
* They are also the choices you refuse to make.
* Your character is revealed as much by your restraints as by your actions.

Even biologically:

* A cell is defined by its membrane.
* The membrane is literally a distinction between self and not-self.
* Without that boundary, the cell ceases to be a cell.

This connects to a theme you’ve explored before: meaning through subtraction.

Sometimes adding information increases confusion. Removing possibilities increases resolution.

A detective narrows suspects.
A scientist rules out hypotheses.
A golfer eliminates swing thoughts until one useful cue remains.
A writer cuts words until the signal becomes visible.

In mathematics, a set is often defined by what is excluded. In logic, negation creates structure. In art, negative space shapes the image.

So when you say:

We are just as much what we aren’t as what we are.

I hear something like:

Identity is a boundary condition, not merely a collection of attributes.

The shape of a life is determined by both its occupied space and the space it leaves empty.

An oak is not merely the tree it became. It is also the countless branches it never grew.

A parent is partly the person they are, and partly the versions of themselves they set aside for their children.

A civilization is partly what it builds, and partly what it refuses to tolerate.

And at a deeper level, every finite thing owes its shape to exclusion. If it included everything, it would have no distinguishable form at all.

In that sense, absence isn’t the opposite of presence.

It’s one of the ingredients that makes presence possible.